>>Dear all, Just wanted to warn people of kunda=
lini syndrome based on my recent experience of a patient of mine. I am doin=
g a psychiatry job at present, and have been involved in the care of someon=
e who seems to think she has had a spontaneous awakening of their kundalini=
 since childhood. This has involved out-of-body experiences and surges of e=
nergy in the body. She is not of Indian origin and had never heard of kunda=
lini until her symptoms started and she searched for an explanation. We hav=
e not been able to find anything physically wrong with her (all tests norma=
l)- so it might be that this is due to deranged kundalini. Many people we c=
all mentally ill describe themselves as having a spiritual crisis, or unwan=
ted spontaneous kundalini awakening- this has triggered interest and resear=
ch into this topic in mainstream psychiatry. Unfortunately these patients a=
re not well-understood by western medicine, and as we have no treatments fo=
r deranged kundalini,
 we struggle to help them. Many yogis try to forcibly=
 waken the kundalini. My experience with this lady confirmed my feeling tha=
t kundalini should not be forcibly wakened. This woman wants to kill hersel=
f at times because the suffering from the deranged energy is so bad. She fe=
els it will consume her, and it is something she cannot escape from. I wond=
ered what solution there could be to her problem. The logical one was to pr=
ay to the Divine Mother, who manifests as the kundalini to relieve the suff=
ering of this woman- and either cure her, or give her the strength to bear =
this. May I request that the good samaritans among you pray for her, and fo=
r others like her (whom we may not know of)- their suffering really is piti=
able. And let us be careful in our sadhana so as not to end up in this situ=
ation ourselves. Perhaps this is why the bhakti marga is the safest. It is =
perhaps safest to say "let me be your instrument" and leave the kundalini r=
ising bit to
 God's will. Om Dum Durgayai Namaha Aparna 
