r all, Just wanted to warn people of kundalini syndrome based on my recent =
experience of a patient of mine. I am doing a psychiatry job at present, an=
d have been involved in the care of someone who seems to think she has had =
a spontaneous awakening of their kundalini since childhood. This has involv=
ed out-of-body experiences and surges of energy in the body. She is not of =
Indian origin and had never heard of kundalini until her symptoms started a=
nd she searched for an explanation. We have not been able to find anything =
physically wrong with her (all tests normal)- so it might be that this is d=
ue to deranged kundalini. Many people we call mentally ill describe themsel=
ves as having a spiritual crisis, or unwanted spontaneous kundalini awakeni=
ng- this has triggered interest and research into this topic in mainstream =
psychiatry. Unfortunately these patients are not well-understood by western=
 medicine, and as we have no treatments
 for deranged kundalini, we struggl=
e to help them. Many yogis try to forcibly waken the kundalini. My experien=
ce with this lady confirmed my feeling that kundalini should not be forcibl=
y wakened. This woman wants to kill herself at times because the suffering =
from the deranged energy is so bad. She feels it will consume her, and it i=
s something she cannot escape from. I wondered what solution there could be=
 to her problem. The logical one was to pray to the Divine Mother, who mani=
fests as the kundalini to relieve the suffering of this woman- and either c=
ure her, or give her the strength to bear this. May I request that the good=
 samaritans among you pray for her, and for others like her (whom we may no=
t know of)- their suffering really is pitiable. And let us be careful in ou=
r sadhana so as not to end up in this situation ourselves. Perhaps this is =
why the bhakti marga is the safest. It is perhaps safest to say "let me be =
your
 instrument" and leave the kundalini rising bit to God's will. Om Dum =
